name.text: Reaction Forces and Free Body Diagram. Level 5.Question ID #1

questiontext.text:
A simply supported beam of length 200 cm is shown in the figure above. There are two supports, one at either end of the beam, hence reaction forces R1 and R2. There is a force of 10 N acting at a point 70 cm along the beam. There is a UDL of mass 20 kg between points 20cm and 60 cm along the beam. There is a second UDL of mass 50 kg between points 120 cm and 170 cm along the beam.

The beam also has a weight of 10 N/cm.

By resolving forces and taking moments, determine the value of reaction forces, R1 and R2.

You may assume a value of g of 10.0 m/s2.

Give your answer to 2 d.p.

R1: {1:NUMERICAL:=1304:13.04#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N
R2: {1:NUMERICAL:=1406:14.06#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N

generalfeedback.text:
For the purposes of calculating reaction forces and moments, one can use the Equivalent Free Body Diagram, where a uniformly distributed load (UDL) is considered to be a point load at its centre of mass, as per the image below:

The beam can be treated like a UDL, meaning that there are effectively 3 UDLs and one point load to consider in this question, as well as the two reaction forces.

For each UDL in turn, calculate the load value and position (as per the previous questions).

When a system is in equilibrium the total forces and the total moment need to be equal to zero; otherwise the system will be moving or rotating, respectively.

Use the convention that upward forces and anti-clockwise moments are positive, as shown in the diagram below.

In this case taking moments about the left hand corner of the beam, we have:

$$\small\sum$$ Mz=0 $$\rightarrow$$

(2m x R2) - (0.4m x 200N) - (0.7m x 10N) - (1m x 2000N) - (1.45m x 500N) = 0

Hence:

R2 = 1406N.


In this case resolving vertical forces, we have:

$$\small\sum$$ Fy=0 $$\rightarrow$$ R1 + R2 - 200 - 10 -2000 - 500 = 0.

Hence:

R1 = 1304N.


The equation $$\small\sum$$ Fx=0 still holds true in this case, but is not used here as there are no forces with an x-component.

hint.text:
HINT

Don't forget to consider all 6 forces in this case (including the weight of the beam), when constructing the Equivalent Free Body Diagram.

A simply supported beam of length 200 cm is shown in the figure above. There are two supports, one at either end of the beam, hence reaction forces R1 and R2. There is a force of 7 N acting at a point 70 cm along the beam. There is a UDL of mass 15 kg between points 30cm and 60 cm along the beam. There is a second UDL of mass 30 kg between points 170 cm and 200 cm along the beam.

The beam also has a weight of 10 N/cm.

By resolving forces and taking moments, determine the value of reaction forces, R1 and R2.

You may assume a value of g of 10.0 m/s2.

Give your answer to 2 d.p.

R1: {1:NUMERICAL:=1143.3:11.433#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N
R2: {1:NUMERICAL:=1313.7:13.137#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N

generalfeedback.text:
For the purposes of calculating reaction forces and moments, one can use the Equivalent Free Body Diagram, where a uniformly distributed load (UDL) is considered to be a point load at its centre of mass, as per the image below:

The beam can be treated like a UDL, meaning that there are effectively 3 UDLs and one point load to consider in this question, as well as the two reaction forces.

For each UDL in turn, calculate the load value and position (as per the previous questions).

When a system is in equilibrium the total forces and the total moment need to be equal to zero; otherwise the system will be moving or rotating, respectively.

Use the convention that upward forces and anti-clockwise moments are positive, as shown in the diagram below.

In this case taking moments about the left hand corner of the beam, we have:

$$\small\sum$$ Mz=0 $$\rightarrow$$

(2m x R2) - (0.45m x 150N) - (0.7m x 7N) - (1m x 2000N) - (1.85m x 300N) = 0

Hence:

R2 = 1313.7N.


In this case resolving vertical forces, we have:

$$\small\sum$$ Fy=0 $$\rightarrow$$ R1 + R2 - 150 - 7 -2000 - 300 = 0.

Hence:

R1 = 1143.3N.


The equation $$\small\sum$$ Fx=0 still holds true in this case, but is not used here as there are no forces with an x-component.

hint.text:
HINT

Don't forget to consider all 6 forces in this case (including the weight of the beam), when constructing the Equivalent Free Body Diagram.

A simply supported beam of length 200 cm is shown in the figure above. There are two supports, one at either end of the beam, hence reaction forces R1 and R2. There is a force of 6 N acting at a point 70 cm along the beam. There is a UDL of mass 30 kg between points 0cm and 60 cm along the beam. There is a second UDL of mass 30 kg between points 170 cm and 200 cm along the beam.

The beam also has a weight of 10 N/cm.

By resolving forces and taking moments, determine the value of reaction forces, R1 and R2.

You may assume a value of g of 10.0 m/s2.

Give your answer to 2 d.p.

R1: {1:NUMERICAL:=1281.4:12.814#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N
R2: {1:NUMERICAL:=1324.6:13.246#Good job!!~*#Incorrect}N

generalfeedback.text:
For the purposes of calculating reaction forces and moments, one can use the Equivalent Free Body Diagram, where a uniformly distributed load (UDL) is considered to be a point load at its centre of mass, as per the image below:

The beam can be treated like a UDL, meaning that there are effectively 3 UDLs and one point load to consider in this question, as well as the two reaction forces.

For each UDL in turn, calculate the load value and position (as per the previous questions).

When a system is in equilibrium the total forces and the total moment need to be equal to zero; otherwise the system will be moving or rotating, respectively.

Use the convention that upward forces and anti-clockwise moments are positive, as shown in the diagram below.

In this case taking moments about the left hand corner of the beam, we have:

$$\small\sum$$ Mz=0 $$\rightarrow$$

(2m x R2) - (0.3m x 300N) - (0.7m x 6N) - (1m x 2000N) - (1.85m x 300N) = 0

Hence:

R2 = 1324.6N.


In this case resolving vertical forces, we have:

$$\small\sum$$ Fy=0 $$\rightarrow$$ R1 + R2 - 300 - 6 -2000 - 300 = 0.

Hence:

R1 = 1281.4N.


The equation $$\small\sum$$ Fx=0 still holds true in this case, but is not used here as there are no forces with an x-component.

hint.text:
HINT

Don't forget to consider all 6 forces in this case (including the weight of the beam), when constructing the Equivalent Free Body Diagram.

For the purposes of calculating reaction forces and moments, one can use the Equivalent Free Body Diagram, where a uniformly distributed load (UDL) is considered to be a point load at its centre of mass, as per the image below:

The beam can be treated like a UDL, meaning that there are effectively 3 UDLs and one point load to consider in this question, as well as the two reaction forces.

For each UDL in turn, calculate the load value and position (as per the previous questions).

When a system is in equilibrium the total forces and the total moment need to be equal to zero; otherwise the system will be moving or rotating, respectively.

Use the convention that upward forces and anti-clockwise moments are positive, as shown in the diagram below.

In this case taking moments about the left hand corner of the beam, we have:

$$\small\sum$$ Mz=0 $$\rightarrow$$

(2m x R2) - (0.45m x 150N) - (0.7m x 8N) - (1m x 2000N) - (1.5m x 400N) = 0

Hence:

R2 = 1336.55N.


In this case resolving vertical forces, we have:

$$\small\sum$$ Fy=0 $$\rightarrow$$ R1 + R2 - 150 - 8 -2000 - 400 = 0.

Hence:

R1 = 1221.45N.


The equation $$\small\sum$$ Fx=0 still holds true in this case, but is not used here as there are no forces with an x-component.
